<div id="ftn32">
<p><a href="file://lifile01/userdata/aoliver/Redirection/Desktop/LOWY/BOBO%20LO,%20CHINA%20RUSSIA%20GLOBAL%20ORDER/Bobo%20Lo,%20Global%20Order%20in%20the%20Shadow%20of%20the%20Coronavirus%20-%20China,%20Russia%20and%20the%20West,%20FINAL%20270720.doc#_ftnref32" name="_ftn32" title="" id="_ftn32">[32]</a> “I want to remind you that the Congress of Vienna in 1815 and the agreements made at Yalta in 1945, taken with Russia’s very active participation, secured a lasting peace” — Putin address to the Valdai International Discussion Club, 19 September 2013, <a href="http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/19243">http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/19243</a>. Two years later, he pointed to the 1648 Peace of Westphalia (which concluded the Thirty Years’ War), the Congress of Vienna, and Yalta, as proving that peace depended on “securing and maintaining the existing balance of forces” — address to the Valdai International Discussion Club, 22 October 2015, <a href="http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/50548">http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/50548</a>.</p>
