<div id="ftn46">
<p><a href="file://lifile01/userdata/aoliver/Redirection/Desktop/LOWY/BOBO%20LO,%20CHINA%20RUSSIA%20GLOBAL%20ORDER/Bobo%20Lo,%20Global%20Order%20in%20the%20Shadow%20of%20the%20Coronavirus%20-%20China,%20Russia%20and%20the%20West,%20FINAL%20270720.doc#_ftnref46" name="_ftn46" title="" id="_ftn46">[46]</a> Vostok 2018 involved an estimated 300 000 Russian troops, but only 3200 Chinese troops. There was a Chinese contingent in the Tsentr-2019 exercise, along with forces from India, Pakistan, and the former Soviet Central Asian republics.</p>
</div>
<div id="ftn47">
<p><a href="file://lifile01/userdata/aoliver/Redirection/Desktop/LOWY/BOBO%20LO,%20CHINA%20RUSSIA%20GLOBAL%20ORDER/Bobo%20Lo,%20Global%20Order%20in%20the%20Shadow%20of%20the%20Coronavirus%20-%20China,%20Russia%20and%20the%20West,%20FINAL%20270720.doc#_ftnref47" name="_ftn47" title="" id="_ftn47">[47]</a> Russia has sold the S-400 system to India and Turkey, as well as China. Southeast Asia is the biggest growth market for Russian arms, accounting for more than 60 per cent of total exports. See Alexander Kruglov, “Business Booming for Russia’s Arms Traders”, <em>Asia Times</em>, 22 April 2019, <a href="https://asiatimes.com/2019/04/business-booming-for-russias-arms-traders/">https://asiatimes.com/2019/04/business-booming-for-russias-arms-traders/</a>; also Meaghan Tobin, “From Russia with Guns: Why is Southeast Asia Buying Arms From Moscow, Not Washington?”, <em>This Week in Asia</em>, 12 October 2019, <a href="https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/politics/article/3032608/russia-guns-why-southeast-asia-buying-arms-moscow-not-washington">https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/politics/article/3032608/russia-guns-why-southeast-asia-buying-arms-moscow-not-washington</a>.</p>
